Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: * FINANCIAL RECORDS *

[Clerk: MK]
case called at 2:40pm. 
Defendant Kassie E Gehler in court with Attorney William A. Mayer.  ADA Brookellen Teuber appears for the State of Wisconsin.
Attorney Mayer plays a voicemail recording from the Dodge County supervising agent that indicates that the agent believes it is unlikely that an interstate compact will occur in this case because it is a "discretionary" interstate compact, and she does not believe that the State of Arizona will accept the supervision of a Probation term. 
Attorney Mayer indicates that Ms. Gehler's shoulder surgery is now scheduled for October 13th. Attorney Mayer renews his request to have the sentencing scheduled in July 2015.
The Court and counsel discuss scheduling and the possibility of the Court imposing a jail term and having Ms. Gehler serve the sentence now, rather than delaying the sentencing until next July.
Sentencing arguments given by counsel. 
ADA Teuber verifies victim rights compliance. 
Ms. Gehler makes a statement. 

The Court sentences Ms. Gehler to:
--serve twenty days in Jefferson County Jail, (no Huber); to commence tomorrow, September 27, 2014 at 7:00pm. 
--0 days credit for time already served given
--pay fine of $500 plus costs= $908 plus $250 DNA surcharge=$1158, to be paid by 12/31/14; non-payment shall result in entry of a civil judgment 

Felony firearm/voting prohibition warnings are given.
The Court finds that society will not be harmed and that Ms. Gehler will benefit from expungement of this record.  However the Court will not only allow Ms. Gehler to pursue expungement until she reaches the age of 25; thereafter Ms. Gehler may petition the Court for expungement.  At that time, the Court would be looking at any subsequent criminal cases or traffic/forfeiture cases. 
Felony firearm voting/firearms warnings/penalties given. 
recess 3:02pm.
With elements attached.
Conditions of bond include:  Ms. Gehler is to report to the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department for booking today.

[Clerk: MK]
case called at 1:07pm. 
Defendant Kassie E Gehler in court with Attorney William A. Mayer.  ADA Jeffrey Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
Ms. Gehler waives her right to Preliminary Hearing; the Court accepts this waiver and binds her over for Trial.
Service of Information admitted, reading waived.
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; Attorney Mayer verifies that he has reviewed the "Party to A Crime" elements;  a plea of " No Contest " is entered on Count #2; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; the Court accepts plea, finds Ms. Gehler guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

The Court and counsel discuss scheduling. The Defense requests that the Court schedule sentencing in July 2015 when Ms. Gehler is scheduled to complete inpatient treatment in Arizona. Instead, the Court schedules the Sentencing Hearing tomorrow. 
The Court requires a $10,000 signature bond, with conditions: 
--Ms. Gehler is to report to the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department for booking today.
recess 1:20pm. 

NEXT:  schedule Sentencing Hearing tomorrow at 2:30pm.

case called at 10:06am.
Defendant Kassie E Gehler in court.  ADA Jeffrey Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.
This case is scheduled for Initial Appearance today.
Mr. Armachy, who is present in the courtroom gallery, indicates that Ms. Gehler is currently in a one-year treatment program in Arizona.
The Court makes reference to information it received from the Dodge County DA Klomberg that Mr. Armachy appears to be asserting that he is acting as some type of advocate for Ms. Gehler, however DA Klomberg indicates that Mr. Armachy took Ms. Gehler to Arizona without the Dodge County Judge's or DA's approval.

The Court notes that it has read the Criminal Complaint and finds probable cause to exist in the Complaint.
On Motion of ADA Shock, the Court issues a Warrant for the arrest of Ms. Gehler. 
recess 10:10am.

[Clerk: MK]
case called at 1:20pm. 
Defendant Kassie E Gehler not in court.  DA Susan Happ appears for the State of Wisconsin.
DA Happ indicates that she has been informed that Ms. Gehler is currently in a treatment facility.  DA Happ proposes that Initial Appearance be rescheduled in a few weeks, if possible coordinating that date so it coincides with Co-Defendant Nicholas Dambruch's Initial Appearance.
The Court adjourns.  
DA Happ has been given information that Attorney Bill Mayer may be representing Ms. Gehler in this case; Attorney Mayer currently represents Ms. Gehler in a Dodge County matter.
